ll, Suffolk, England":"Tendring Hall, Suffolk, England","Stoke by Nayland, Suffolk, England":"Stoke by Nayland, Suffolk, England","England":"England","Wickhambrook, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Wickhambrook, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Scotland, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Clare, Suffolk, England":"Clare, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mylde","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Helmut, Hans.","German; Flemish and Dutch (also <b>De Milde</b>): nickname from Middle High German <i>milde</i>, Middle Dutch <i>mild(e)</i> ‘kind, gentle, compassionate, generous’.","German: habitational name from Milda in Thuringia."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":6,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705193,"age":15,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","